ce:section.ce:para:
NCD were synthesized from rice straws by hydrothermal treatment as depicted in Scheme 1 . Hydrolysis was performed by exposing rice straw to a diluted hydrochloric acid solution after it had been soaked in NaOH(aq). Treatment with DMSO and TBAA followed by acetic anhydride yielded cellulose diacetate (CDA) from cellulose fibers isolated from rice straw. Dilute NH4OH(aq) was utilized as a passivating agent as an alternative to other expensive and toxic passivating agents, which comprise terminal amine substituents. The optimal quantum yield (QY) of NCD was measured by experimenting with various mass ratios of ammonium hydroxide to CDA, as shown in Fig. 1 . Raising the QY from 7.07 to 24.09 % required changing the NH4OH to CDA mass ratio from 1:0 to 1:15, respectively. When this ratio was raised to 1:20, the QY of NCD would fall even more. To achieve this goal, we investigated the impacts of varying the mass ratio of ammonium hydroxide to crystalline crystalline amorphous silica (CDA) to create NCD with QY values as high as 24.09 %. Initial hydrolysis of cellulose diacetate, followed by condensing short fragments to give NCD, was hypothesized in prior investigations on cellulose degradation and carbonization. CDA is a cellulose derivative that is held together by glycosidic linkages between glucose-like units. Breaking the glycosidic bond and deacetylating CDA in NH4OH(aq) might produce glucose, acetic acid, fructose, and CDA-based intermediate fragmentations [35]. It has been proposed that ammonium hydroxide also generates novel O- and N-based functional groups. The CDA-based intermediate fragmentations were exposed to condensation and carbonization to provide the carbonic architectures of NCD. The key to effectively passivating N onto CD was the nucleophilic substitution of ammonia to the hydroxyl carbon [35]. Those NCD were effectively disseminated spherical nano-scaled particles. Fig. 2 shows that NCD had diameters of 10–25 nm as shown in TEM images. It has been reported that NCD did not have a lattice structure [36]. In contrast to the single band shown in the XRD pattern of carbon dots at 23.43° (owing to their amorphous carbon phase), the XRD of CDA reveals two wide bands at 8.3° and 19.1° [36], which are linked to the unique crystallization phase of CDA ( Fig. 3
). The NCD surface groups were determined by FTIR spectroscopic analysis ( Fig. 4
). FTIR analysis of NCD revealed the presence of NH/OH stretching band at 3048 cm−1, as well as additional stretching bands at 1239 and 724 cm−1, respectively. Those peaks suggest that the N-doping procedure was effective. Sulfur was likely present in the NCD because of the presence of a stretching peak at 1088 cm−1 between sulfur and carbon monoxide (SO3/C-O) [35,36].
